📘 Docker + CMD + ENTRYPOINT + Nginx (Proper Notes)
🧠 1. VM vs Docker (Foundation)
🔹 In Virtual Machines:
Uses systemd
Services managed using:
systemctl start nginx
Services run in background (daemon mode)
🔹 In Docker:
❌ No systemd
❌ No service manager
✅ Docker directly runs a process

👉 Important Rule:

Container runs only if the main process is running (foreground)

🔥 2. Nginx Behavior in Docker
🔹 Default behavior of Nginx
nginx
Runs in background ❌
Container exits immediately ❌
🔹 Correct way in Docker:
nginx -g "daemon off;"
Explanation:
-g → pass global config from CLI
daemon off; → run in foreground

👉 Required to keep container alive

⚡ 3. CMD (Command)
Definition:

CMD defines the default command to run when container starts

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
Behavior:
Can be overridden at runtime
docker run myimage bash

👉 CMD is replaced

⚡ 4. ENTRYPOINT
Definition:

ENTRYPOINT defines the main executable (fixed command)

ENTRYPOINT ["nginx"]
Behavior:
Cannot be easily overridden
Always runs
🔥 5. CMD vs ENTRYPOINT (Core Difference)
Feature	CMD	ENTRYPOINT
Purpose	Default command	Main executable
Override	Yes	No
Flexibility	High	Low
🚀 6. Best Practice (Production)
ENTRYPOINT ["nginx"]
CMD ["-g", "daemon off;"]
Execution:
nginx -g "daemon off;"
🔁 7. Passing Arguments
Command:
docker run myimage -v
Behavior:
ENTRYPOINT → stays (nginx)
CMD → replaced (-g daemon off; → -v)
Final execution:
nginx -v
🔹 8. Meaning of -v

Depends on context:

In Nginx → version
In Docker → volume mount
In general CLI → verbose
🔹 9. Why NOT daemon on
daemon on → runs in background ❌
Container exits immediately ❌

👉 Always use:

daemon off;
🔹 10. Node.js in Docker
Node.js
Not a service
Runs directly in foreground
node app.js

👉 No need for daemon off

🔹 11. Why CMD is Required

👉 Docker does NOT know what to run

Without CMD or ENTRYPOINT:

Container starts
Immediately stops ❌
🔥 12. PID 1 Concept
First process in container = PID 1
This is your main app (nginx/node)

👉 If it stops:

Container stops
🧠 13. Key Rules to Remember
Docker runs process, not services
Must run in foreground
One main process per container
CMD = default command
ENTRYPOINT = fixed command
🎯 Interview Answer (Perfect)

“Docker does not use systemd, so it directly runs the application process defined in CMD or ENTRYPOINT. The process must run in the foreground to keep the container alive. For Nginx, we use ‘daemon off’, while Node.js runs directly since it already runs in the foreground.”

⚡ Quick Revision (1-minute)
VM → systemd manages services
Docker → runs process directly
Nginx → needs daemon off
CMD → default, replaceable
ENTRYPOINT → fixed
PID 1 → main process
Container stops if process stops
